1. Introduction¶

1.1 Background¶

Data Science is a quickly growing field. According to the Bureau of Labor Statistics, the field (computer and information research scientists) is expected to grow by 22% between 2020 and 2030, which is much faster than average.

The purpose of this tutorial is to examine the data science job market in the U.S. and gain insights about the kinds of jobs, companies, and sectors make up the job market, and what kinds of factors impact job salaries and company ratings.

1.2 Setup¶

  • Folium: used for visualizing data on a map.
  • Matplotlib: used for all other plots.
  • Numpy: used for supporting data.
  • Pandas: used for storing and processing data.
  • Re: regular expression package used for cleaning data.
  • Scikit-learn: used for training a predictive model from the data.
  • Wordcloud: used for visualizing frequency of text.
In [1]:

2. Data Collection¶

2.1 About the Data¶

The dataset used in this tutorial was downloaded from kaggle (https://www.kaggle.com/andrewmvd/data-scientist-jobs). The dataset includes 3909 data science job listings in 2020 scraped from Glassdoor, with 17 features such as job title, salary estimate, company name, location, etc. The set includes entries for jobs in the United States and the United Kingdom (but we will focus on the entries in the United States, which makes up a vast majority of the entries).

2.2 Loading the Data¶

The first step is to load the data. First, download the CSV from kaggle into the same directory as your code. Then, we load the CSV into a pandas dataframe for easy viewing and manipulation.

2.3 Data Wrangling¶

Irrelevant/Missing Data¶

The pandas dataframe has an unnamed column that is exactly the same as the index column. We can drop this column to declutter the dataframe.

As we can see in the preview of the data above, there are several values of -1/-1.0 where it doesn't make sense as a real value (such as rating, year founded, industry). Assuming that values of -1 indicate null values, we want to replace them with NaNs so that they don't affect any numerical analysis we do.

We won't change the "Unknown" values in the type of ownership or Revenue columns, since those are categorical variables.

In [3]:
jobs = jobs.drop('Unnamed: 0', axis=1)
jobs = jobs.replace({-1: np.nan, '-1': np.nan}) # replace -1s with NaN

Since we are interested in the U.S. job market, we also want to remove entries for jobs outside of the U.S. Looking at the data, we can see that there are 4 entries for jobs in the U.K., so let's drop those rows.

In [4]:
not_us_rows = []
for i in jobs.index:
    if 'United Kingdom' in jobs.loc[i]['Location']:
        not_us_rows.append(i)

jobs = jobs.drop(not_us_rows)

Job Titles¶

Looking at the value counts for the Job Title column, we see that there are 2076 unique job title values. There are several job titles that include extra information after commas, dashes, slahes, or in parentheses.

In [5]:

Out[5]:

Senior Data Scientist                                            91

                                                               ... 
Data Analyst 3                                                    1
Splunk SME / Data Analyst _ TXho_                                 1
VP, Data Scientist                                                1
Research Scientist — Machine Learning                             1
Business Analytics Manager, Partnerships and Startup Program      1
Name: Job Title, Length: 2076, dtype: int64

In order to reduce the number of unique values in the Job Title column, I removed anything that came after a comma. What this means is that we're considering things like "Data Scientist" and "Data Scientist, Product Analysis" to be the same job title. I also found that there were several job titles like "Data Scientist II" or "Data Scientist 2". According to this article, I/1 corresponds to entry level positions, II/2 to senior positions, and III/3 to principal positions. I replaced these job titles with their corresponding fully spelled-out job titles.

In [6]:
jobs['Job Title'] = jobs['Job Title'].str.strip() # strip extra whitespace
jobs['Job Title'] = jobs['Job Title'].str.title() # change all to title case
jobs['Job Title'] = jobs['Job Title'].replace('\(.*\)', '', regex=True) # get rid of specifications in paretheses
jobs['Job Title'] = jobs['Job Title'].replace(',.*', '', regex=True) # get rid of secondary job title after comma
jobs['Job Title'] = jobs['Job Title'].replace('\s?(-|—).*', '', regex=True) # get rid of secondary job title after dash
jobs['Job Title'] = jobs['Job Title'].replace('\s?/.*', '', regex=True) # get rid of alternate job title after slash
jobs['Job Title'] = jobs['Job Title'].replace('\ASr(\.)?', 'Senior', regex=True) # replace Sr/Sr. w/ Senior

jobs['Job Title'] = jobs['Job Title'].replace('([\w\s]*)\s(Iii|3)$', 'Principal \\1', regex=True) # replace 'X Iii' w 'Principal X'
jobs['Job Title'] = jobs['Job Title'].replace('([\w\s]*)\s(Ii|2)$', 'Senior \\1', regex=True) # replace 'X Ii' w 'Senior X'
jobs['Job Title'] = jobs['Job Title'].replace('([\w\s]*)\s(I|1)$', '\\1', regex=True) # replace 'X I' w 'X'

From that, we've nearly halved the number of unique values, and the top 5 job titles now have much higher frequencies than before.

Salary Estimate¶

At the moment, the Salary Estimate column looks difficult to perform calculations on (string values, ranges of values, etc.) Let's take a look at the kind of values it contains:

In [8]:
jobs['Salary Estimate'].value_counts()
Out[8]:
$93K-$151K (Glassdoor est.)         62
$113K-$180K (Glassdoor est.)        61
$71K-$122K (Glassdoor est.)         60
$111K-$175K (Glassdoor est.)        60
$119K-$147K (Glassdoor est.)        44
                                    ..
$34-$53 Per Hour(Glassdoor est.)     7
$99K-$173K (Glassdoor est.)          6
$10-$26 Per Hour(Glassdoor est.)     3
$146K-$175K (Glassdoor est.)         3
$41K-$74K (Glassdoor est.)           1
Name: Salary Estimate, Length: 148, dtype: int64

Here we can see that there are some salary estimates reported as per-hour values. Since we are interested in salaried positions, we want to remove these.

In order to make calculations with salary easier, we will also want to get rid of the ranges of values, and convert the valus into integers instead of strings. I chose to just take the average of the low and high estimates.

In [9]:
# getting salary estimate midpoints
salary_avg = []
per_hour_rows = []
for i in jobs.index:
    salary_est = jobs.loc[i]['Salary Estimate']
    match = re.search('(\d*)K-\$(\d*)', salary_est) # extract lower and upper estimate
    if match != None:
        average = ((int(match.group(1)) + int(match.group(2))) / 2) * 1000
        salary_avg.append(average) 
    else:
        if 'Per Hour' in salary_est:
            per_hour_rows.append(i) # add per-hour salary rows to a list to drop later
            
jobs = jobs.drop(per_hour_rows) # drop per-hour salary entries
jobs = jobs.reset_index(drop=True) # reset index
jobs.insert(3, 'Avg Salary Estimate', salary_avg) # insert salary averages

Company Name¶

Currently, the company name contains a newline character and a number that seems to be exactly the same as the rating. Let's remove the newline and rating from the company names so that our visualizations won't include them later on.

In [10]:
jobs['Company Name'] = jobs['Company Name'].replace('\n\d\.\d', '', regex=True)

Salaries by Job Title¶

Let's see if there's any difference in estimated salary across the top 10 job titles.

In [16]:
# get only rows where job title is in top 10
top_ten_titles = list(jobs['Job Title'].value_counts()[:10].to_dict().keys())
top_ten_jobs = jobs[jobs['Job Title'].isin(top_ten_titles)] 
top_ten_jobs = top_ten_jobs[['Job Title', 'Avg Salary Estimate']]

# get median, min, and max salary per job title
top_ten_jobs_salaries = top_ten_jobs.groupby('Job Title').min()
top_ten_jobs_salaries = top_ten_jobs_salaries.rename({'Avg Salary Estimate': 'Min'}, axis=1)
top_ten_jobs_salaries['Median'] = top_ten_jobs.groupby('Job Title').median()['Avg Salary Estimate'].values
top_ten_jobs_salaries['Max'] = top_ten_jobs.groupby('Job Title').max()['Avg Salary Estimate'].values
In [17]:
ax = top_ten_jobs_salaries.plot.bar(figsize=(9, 7))
ax.set_title('Estimated Salary for Top 10 Most Common Data Science Job Titles')
ax.set_xlabel('Job Title')
ax.set_ylabel('Salary (in dollars)')
ax.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))
Out[17]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7f7f3e68e2b0>

From this graph, we can see a few key differences between the estimated salary across job titles.

  • Scientists and Senior Scientists, while having similar median and minimum salaries as the other job titles, seem to have much lower maximum estimates.
  • Data Scientists and Senior Data Scientists, however, seem to have higher median and maximum salary estimates than Data Analysts and Data Egnineers (and their respective Senior positions).
  • Data Engineers and Senior Data Engineers have comparable minimum salaries as Data Analysts and Data Scientists, but have lower median and maximum salary estimates.
  • Machine Learning Engineers have the highest minimum salary estimate, and the median and maximum salary estimates are also on the higher end.

The difference between the salary estimates of Data Analysts, Data Engineers, and Data Scientists compared to their corresponding senior positions is not as expected. Many of the estimates are the same, or the Senior position actually has a lower salary estimate. This is likely because some of the job positions that don't specify seniority are actually intended for senior/principal positions, but is not described in the job title.

From the chart above, we see that Agriculture and Forestry sector has the highest median salary, but doesn't have a very high maximum salary. Estimated Salary by Location (State)¶

In [24]:
locations = jobs[['State', 'Avg Salary Estimate']]
locations_salaries = locations.groupby('State').min()
locations_salaries = locations_salaries.rename({'Avg Salary Estimate': 'Min'}, axis=1)
locations_salaries['Median'] = locations.groupby('State').median()['Avg Salary Estimate'].values
locations_salaries['Max'] = locations.groupby('State').max()['Avg Salary Estimate'].values
In [25]:
ax = locations_salaries.plot.bar(figsize=(9,7))
ax.set_title('Estimated Salary by State')
ax.set_xlabel('State')
ax.set_ylabel('Salary (in dollars)')
ax.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))
Out[25]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7f7f3e52c820>

The graph above is nice but isn't very useful, since the cost of living can vary greatly by state. An example is California, which has the highest median and maximum estimated salary, but is also notorious for its incredibly high cost of living. Without accounting for cost of living, we can't show for sure which states offer the highest salaries.

I used cost of living indexes for 2021, taken from here: https://meric.mo.gov/data/cost-living-data-series. The cost indexes are normalized by the average cost of living across the U.S., which has a value of 100. Values greater than 100 indicate higher than average costs of living, while values less than 100 indicate lower than average costs of living. Since we only have data for a few states (10), I just entered the cost of living indexes manually into a list. If we had salary data for all 50 states, it would probably be more efficient to scrape the indexes from the website.

I normalize the salaries by dividing the median salary per state by the state's corresponding cost index.

In [26]:
locations_salaries['Cost Index'] = [107.0, 146.9, 106.6, 101.5, 90.5, 118.3, 143.7, 92.9, 100.5, 92.6]

# normalize salaries
locations_salaries['Normalized'] = locations_salaries['Median'] / locations_salaries['Cost Index']

ax = locations_salaries['Normalized'].plot.bar(figsize=(9, 7))
ax.set_title('Normalized Median Salary by State')
ax.set_xlabel('State')
ax.set_ylabel('Normalized Salary')
ax.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))
Out[26]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7f7f341506d0>

From the chart above, we see that

  • Facebook has the highest median estimated salary
  • Staffigo Technical Services has the lowest median estimated salary (but one of the highest maximum salaries!)
  • Southwest Research Institute has the lowest maximum estimated salary, which may be related to the fact that it is a non-profit.
  • There is not a huge difference in minimum estimated salary across these companies.

However, there is a possibility that these salary estimates are skewed due to the types of job listings the companies had up when the data was scraped. If a company has a lot of entry-level job positions in the data, their average salary would likely be lower than a company that have more senior or principal job positions. This is true for all the salary analyses we will do later, but is especially true when grouping by company (since the number of entries per group is small).

Best Companies by Salary and Rating¶

I wanted to find the best companies overall by taking into account both salary and rating. To do this, I first normalize both median salary and average ratings by company. I then combine the normalized salary and ratings into a company "score" by taking the mean of the two normalized values. This way, both salary and company rating are equally important; if you think one is more important than the other, you can weight the score accordingly (and may get different top companies!)

In [47]:
# get median salary by company
companies = jobs[['Company Name', 'Avg Salary Estimate', 'Rating']]
salaries = companies[['Company Name', 'Avg Salary Estimate']].groupby('Company Name').median() 

# join median salary and ratings on company name
ratings = companies[['Company Name', 'Rating']].drop_duplicates()
companies = ratings.set_index('Company Name').join(salaries, how='inner')

# normalize salary and ratings
companies = companies.rename({'Avg Salary Estimate': 'Median Salary'}, axis=1)
companies['Rating Norms'] = (companies['Rating'] - companies['Rating'].mean()) / companies['Rating'].std()
companies['Median Salary Norms'] = (companies['Median Salary'] - companies['Median Salary'].mean()) / companies['Median Salary'].std()

# score company by the mean of salary and rating z scores
companies['Score'] = (companies['Rating Norms'] + companies['Median Salary Norms']) / 2

companies = companies.sort_values('Score', ascending=False)
companies[:10].join(jobs[['Company Name', 'Sector', 'Type of ownership', 'Headquarters', 'Size']].drop_duplicates().set_index('Company Name'), how='inner')

4. Machine Learning¶

Now that we've taken a look at the various factors affecting job salaries and company ratings, let's see if we can train a machine learning model to predict them.

4.1 Salary¶

For training a model to predict salary, I used only the features that might have an effect on salary. Even though we saw earlier that there is little correlation between salary and company rating, I included it as an input feature anyway; the model should figure out whether there is a relationship between them.

Since many of the relevant features are categorical, I used pd.get_dummies() to convert categorical features into one-hot vector representations. However, because there are so many unique values for Job Title, Company Name, and Location, we end up with an input vector of length 2788.

Ideally, we would probably want to reduce the unique values in the Job Title category much further (I left quite a bit of noise in that category when I cleaned the data in section 2).

This model is doing pretty poorly. This is likely because seniority of job position is an important predictor of salary. However, in our data, seniority can only be expressed in the job title - but as we saw earlier during our exploration of the job titles, seniority is likely not properly indicated in many job titles (which resulted in occurences such as 'Data Analyst' having a higher median salary than 'Senior Data Analyst'). Another issue is that the job title feature is too noisy; there are too many unique job titles, many of which have very few instances and very little differentiation from other job titles. Those job titles should probably be merged into one of the larger job title groups.

The model is at least doing much better than simply guessing the most common salary value (68500). However, this is not surprising because there are many unqiue salary values and the most common value accounts for only approximately 3% of the data.

5. Conclusion¶

From the data exploration and analysis, we were able to identify some key insights about the Data Science job market. Jobs labeled as "Data Scientists" seem to have a higher median salary than "Data Analysts" or "Data Engineers". Jobs labeled as just "Scientist" have comparable median salaries but much lower maximum salaries. The majority of data science jobs are in the Information Technology and Business sectors, and are located in California and Texas. However, working in Delaware is likely to give the highest salary compared to living costs.

The majority of the top 10 companies by number of data science jobs as well as the top 10 companies by salary/rating are public or private companies in the Information Technology sector. However, the companies with the most jobs tend to have 200+ employees, whereas the companies with the best overal salary/ratings tend to have 1-200 employees. Company size seems to be the best differentiator between company ratings, with companies with 1-200 employees having higher than average ratings while companies with 200+ employees have lower than average ratings. Median job salary, on the other hand, doesn't seem to be correlated with company ratings at all. In fact, the sector/type of company with the highest ratings, Education and College/Universities respectively, also consistently has the lowest median job salary.

However, we were not able to create a good model for predicting job salary or company ratings. This may be because the data is simply not easily separable. Another factor that may have reduced model strenght is the categorical features with a high number of unique values. Reducing the number of unique values ond making sure that values are accurate could possibly improve model accuracy. Obtaining numerical values for revenue and size instead of relying on categorical bins could also improve the model accuracy.

In [ ]:
